ic <i>gall</i> ‘foreigner’ + <i>Gaidheal</i> ‘Gael’. From the 8th century or before it was a province of Anglian Northumbria. In the 9th century it was settled by mixed Gaelic-Norse inhabitants from the Hebrides and Isle of Man."],"variants":[{"name":"Gallaway","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Galloway  ."]},{"name":"Galway","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: in most cases, probably a variant of Scottish   Galloway  , rather than from the city or county in Connacht (habitational names are rare in Ireland). During the Middle Ages Galways were wealthy merchants on the south coast of Ireland, but now the name there is largely confined to Ulster."]}]},{"name":"Eve","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["vernacular form of the name borne in the Bible by the first woman, created from one of Adam's ribs (Genesis 2:22). It derives, via Latin <i>Eva</i>, from Hebrew <i>Havva</i>, which is considered to be a variant of the vocabulary word <i>hayya</i> ‘living’ or ‘animal’. Adam gave names to all the animals (Genesis 2:19–20) and then to his wife, who was ‘the mother of all living’ (Genesis 3:20)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Eve Amabilia de Galloway was born about 1194, in Altyre House, Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom. She married Richard Comyn Lord Of Badenoch in 1215, in Badenoch, Inverness-shire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1280, in Scotland, at the age of 87, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"ABT 1194–1280":"umbes 1194–1280","1194–1249":"1194–1249","1215–1275":"1215–1275","1220–1296":"1220–1296","1225–1289":"1225–1289","1194–1280":"1194–1280","1220":"1220","July 1249":"juuli 1249","1275":"1275","1296":"1296","1194":"1194","1280":"1280","ABT 1194":"umbes 1194","1249":"1249","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","from 1215 to 1223":"1215 kuni 1223","1289":"1289","about 1225":"umbes 1225","about 1275":"umbes 1275","Badenoch, Invernes